# Q-SYS Lua Script Architecture

## 0. Core Philosophy

> **"Lean code + rich debug output."**  
> Every significant action, state change, and interaction must be logged.  
> An empty debug window is a useless one.

**Target metrics when refactoring:**
- 50–70% line reduction from verbose implementations ( this is a target but reducation can be more if possible)
- Script stays under ~1000 lines for most controllers
- Every user interaction visible in the debug console

---

## 1. No OOP / Class Pattern

**OOP must never be used.** Every Q-SYS control script is a **singleton by nature** — one script context, one set of `Controls.*`, one set of `Component.GetComponents()` results. There is never more than one instance per file.

**Do not use** `setmetatable`, `__index`, `.new()`, `self:`, or `self.`. It adds ceremony with no benefit.

```lua
-- ❌ AVOID
MyController = {}
MyController.__index = MyController
function MyController.new() return setmetatable({}, MyController) end
function MyController:setRoute(input, output) ... end

-- ✅ CORRECT — flat module, local state
local components = { router = nil, invalid = {} }
local state = { power = false }

local function setRoute(input, output, source) ... end
```

---

## 2. Standard File Structure

Follow this section order in every script:

```
[ Header comment ]    -- name, author, version, brief description
[ Configuration ]     -- data tables: room maps, preset lists, device lists
[ Controls ]          -- local controls = { name = Controls.name, ... }
[ Utilities ]         -- isArr, setProp, bind, bindArray, tableContains, etc.
[ Config ]            -- roomName, debug, clearString constants
[ State ]             -- components {}, state {}, and any per-script flags
[ Debug ]             -- local function debugPrint(str)
[ Functions ]         -- all local functions in dependency order (callees before callers)
[ Events ]            -- local function registerEvents()
[ Init ]              -- local function init()  (with === phase markers)
[ Public API ]        -- GlobalName = { exposed functions } for cross-script calls
[ Start ]             -- pcall wrapper that calls init()
```

---

## 3. Utility Functions (use everywhere)

Include these verbatim at the top of every script:

```lua
local function isArr(t)
    return type(t) == "table" and t[1] ~= nil
end

-- Guards against redundant writes, feedback loops, and race conditions
local function setProp(ctrl, prop, val)
    if not ctrl or ctrl[prop] == val then return end
    ctrl[prop] = val
end

local function bind(ctrl, handler)
    if not ctrl or not handler then return false end
    local ok = pcall(function() ctrl.EventHandler = handler end)
    return ok
end

local function bindArray(ctrls, handler)
    if not ctrls or not handler then return 0 end
    local array = isArr(ctrls) and ctrls or { ctrls }
    local count = 0
    for i, ctrl in ipairs(array) do
        if bind(ctrl, function(ctl)
            local ok, err = pcall(handler, i, ctl)
            if not ok then print("Handler error [index " .. i .. "]: " .. tostring(err)) end
        end) then
            count = count + 1
        end
    end
    return count
end
```

**Why `setProp()` matters:** Prevents redundant Q-SYS control updates (expensive), guards against feedback loops, and acts as insurance against race conditions.

